5 2. Moneys in the fund may be used only for:
6 a. Consultation with environmental scientists or engineers, industry specialists, or
7 others for relevant services to analyze or implement mitigation required from the
8 impact of development; and
9 b. Creation, restoration, or mitigation of similar habitat affected by the construction
10 or operation of an energy conversion or transmission facility. Mitigation of
11 adverse impacts from development under this section shall be conducted in the
12 following order of priority:
13 (1) The area immediately impacted by the development;
14 (2) The county impacted by the development;
15 (3) The region impacted by the development; and
16 (4) Other areas within the state.; and
17 c. Purchasing and maintaining easements or leaseholds.
18 3. The commissioner is not subject to chapter 54-44.4 when contracting for services
19 under this chapter.
20 4. In consultation with the federal environmental law impact review committee, the
21 commissioner shall adopt rules pursuant to chapter 28-32 to implement the provisions
22 of this section.
23 5. Easements or leaseholds purchased by a person to mitigate adverse environmental
24 effects of the construction or operation of an energy conversion or transmission facility
25 under chapter 49-22 must be limited to the operational life of the facility as defined
26 under chapter 49-22. Any payment made to mitigate adverse environmental effects of
27 the construction or operation of an energy conversion or transmission facility under
28 chapter 49-22 must be made to the commissioner who shall deposit the payment into
29 the environmental impact mitigation fund. Prior to the public service commission
30 issuing a permit or certificate to an applicant under chapter 49-22, the commissioner
31 shall notify the public service commission of mitigation efforts under this section to
